    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>


<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      How many 4-letter codes can be formed using the first 10 letters of the english alphabet, if no letter can be repeated? 
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>


<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      How many 5-digit telephone numbers can be constructed using the digits 0 to 9, if each number starts with 6 7 and 
      no digit appears more than once? 
    </p>
    <hint>
      <p>
        <m>1 \times 1 \times 8 \times 7 \times 6 = ------</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        digits 6 and 7 are fixed at <m>5^{th}</m> and <m>4^{th}</m> place and no repetion is allowed hence, 
        we can have 8 choices of digits to place at <m>3^{rd}</m> place,  7 choices of digits to place at <m>2^{nd}</m> place, and 
        6 choices of digits to place at <m>1^{st}</m> place.
      </p>
    </hint>
  </statement>
</exercise>


<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
     A coin is tossed 3 times and the outcomes are recorded. How many possible outcomes are there? 
    </p>
  </statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
      There are two outcomes for every toss of a coin, Head or Tail. 
      <me>
        \begin{array}{c|c|c} 
        \circ &amp; I  &amp; II   &amp; III \\ \hline 
        i.  &amp; H  &amp;  H &amp; H \\  
        ii.  &amp; H  &amp;  H &amp; T \\ 
        iii.  &amp; H  &amp;  T &amp; H \\   
        iv.  &amp; H  &amp;  T &amp; T \\     
        v.  &amp; T  &amp;  H &amp; T \\  
        vi.  &amp; T  &amp; T &amp; H \\  
        vii.  &amp; T  &amp;  H &amp; H \\ 
        viii.  &amp; T  &amp;  T &amp; T \\      
       \end{array}
      </me>

    </p>
  </hint>
</exercise>


